==============================
Kubernetes Storage Notes
(PV, PVC, Dynamic Provisioning)
==============================


1. Persistent Volume (PV)
-------------------------

Persistent Volume (PV) is the actual storage resource in the Kubernetes cluster.

In Amazon EKS, storage is usually backed by AWS EBS volumes.

Example PV YAML

apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolume
metadata:
  name: my-pv
spec:
  capacity:
    storage: 1Gi
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
  storageClassName: ebs-storage


Check PV

kubectl get pv



2. Persistent Volume Claim (PVC)
--------------------------------

Persistent Volume Claim (PVC) is a request for storage made by a Pod.

A Pod does not use PV directly.

Flow:

Pod → PVC → PV → Storage


Example PVC YAML

apiVersion: v1
kind: PersistentVolumeClaim
metadata:
  name: my-pvc
spec:
  accessModes:
    - ReadWriteOnce
  storageClassName: ebs-storage
  resources:
    requests:
      storage: 1Gi


Create PVC

kubectl apply -f pvc.yml

Check PVC

kubectl get pvc



3. Dynamic Volume Provisioning
------------------------------

Normally:

Admin → PV create
User → PVC create

But with Dynamic Provisioning, Kubernetes automatically creates a PV when a PVC is created.

This works through StorageClass.


Example StorageClass

apiVersion: storage.k8s.io/v1
kind: StorageClass
metadata:
  name: ebs-storage
provisioner: ebs.csi.aws.com
volumeBindingMode: WaitForFirstConsumer
reclaimPolicy: Delete


Create StorageClass

kubectl apply -f sc.yml

Check StorageClass

kubectl get sc



4. volumeBindingMode
--------------------

Immediate

volumeBindingMode: Immediate

The volume is created immediately when the PVC is created.


WaitForFirstConsumer

volumeBindingMode: WaitForFirstConsumer

The volume is created only when a Pod using the PVC is scheduled.

Flow:

PVC Created
   ↓
Pod Scheduled
   ↓
PV Created



5. reclaimPolicy
----------------


Delete

reclaimPolicy: Delete

Flow:

PVC Deleted
   ↓
PV Deleted
   ↓
Storage Deleted


Retain

reclaimPolicy: Retain

Flow:

PVC Deleted
   ↓
PV Remains
   ↓
Storage Remains

Data is not deleted. Manual cleanup is required.



6. StatefulSet Behavior
-----------------------

In StatefulSet, pods are created and deleted sequentially (one by one).

Example:

pod-0
pod-1
pod-2


Delete Pod

kubectl delete pod pod-1


Kubernetes recreates the pod with the same identity and storage.


Check Pods

kubectl get pods



7. Important Commands
--------------------


Check Storage Resources

kubectl get pv
kubectl get pvc
kubectl get sc


Describe Resources

kubectl describe pv
kubectl describe pvc



Delete Commands
---------------


Delete All PVC

kubectl delete pvc --all


Delete All PV

kubectl delete pv --all


Delete All Pods

kubectl delete pods --all


Delete Specific Pod

kubectl delete pod pod-name



==============================
Summary
==============================

PV  → Actual storage
PVC → Storage request
StorageClass → Storage configuration
Dynamic Provisioning → Automatic PV creation
Delete Policy → Storage deleted
Retain Policy → Storage preserved
